{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2317"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2317"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.08,0.44,0.04,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84643"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with a two year history of intermittent rectal bleeding. He describes the painless passage of a small amount of fresh blood whenever he passes a constipated stool. The episodes of bleeding have become more frequent recently and the bleeding can even occur when he is passing a normal soft stool. He is otherwise in good health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternal haemorrhoids are noted on rectal examination. These are visible beyond the anal verge on unaided inspection and can be manually reduced. The rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dietary modification with the addition of more fibre","Stool softeners","Rubber band ligation","Sclerotherapy","Haemorrhoidectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHaemorrhoids can be classified into the following Grades:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI protrusion into the anal canal, occasional bleeding, but no prolapse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII protrusion beyond the anal verge with straining or defection and spontaneous reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII spontaneous protrusion or as the result of straining, requiring manual reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV permanent prolapse and unable to be reduced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment tends to be based on the Grade:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI conservative measures (high fibre diet, increased fluid intake, stool softeners)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII conservative measures and perhaps rubber band ligation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII above, plus haemorrhoidectomy for severe symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV haemorroidectomy; this group often including patients with acute thrombosis or strangulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese are approximations - and treatment will vary according to the severity of the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDietary modification with the addition of more fibre might be all the patient requires for Grade I or II haemorrhoids - but these have prolapsed beyond the anal verge and will require something more active. Stool softeners might help his episodes of constipation - but he has Grade III haemorrhoids, worsening symptoms and will probably require something more active. Sclerotherapy might be suitable for Grades I or II haemorrhoids, but has largely been replaced by other treatments, such as high fibre diet, stool softeners and \u003Cstrong\u003Erubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E. Surgery is reserved for Grade IV haemorrhoids or patients with Grade III and severe symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with haemorrhoids can get good symptomatic relief through simple strategies including high fibre diet and stool softeners.","Further therapeutic options are available, depending on the severity of symptoms and the grade of haemorrhoids."],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician 2018; 97:172-79."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84643"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2317"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84643"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T08:36:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T08:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2317"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102179"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"se